{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538643"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16257"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16257"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.03,0.08,0.05,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8948"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111069"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8948"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16257"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93190"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2112"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"},{"type":"tags","id":"4102"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45094"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111069"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset lower abdominal pain that began two hours ago. The pain is severe and localised to the right iliac fossa. She reports regular menstrual cycles and her last period was two weeks ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications except for the combined oral contraceptive pill.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale and distressed. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is tender in the right iliac fossa with guarding. Investigations reveal haemoglobin 92 g/L (115-160), falling from 115 g/L four hours ago, white cell count 8.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0), and C-reactive protein 4 mg/L (\u003C5). Beta human chorionic gonadotropin is negative. Transvaginal ultrasound shows a 4 cm right ovarian cyst with complex echogenic features and a large amount of free fluid in the pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transvaginal aspiration of the cyst","Empiric antibiotics","Expectant management with oral analgesia","Observation and serial haemoglobin measurements","Diagnostic laparoscopy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with a ruptured haemorrhagic ovarian cyst causing significant intraperitoneal bleeding. The key features supporting this diagnosis are the negative pregnancy test, ultrasound findings showing a complex cyst with free fluid, and dropping haemoglobin level. While patients on the combined oral contraceptive pill typically do not ovulate, functional cysts can still occur. The normal white cell count and C-reactive protein help exclude appendicitis as a differential diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step given the evidence of ongoing bleeding (dropping haemoglobin) and haemodynamic changes (tachycardia, hypotension). This allows both definitive diagnosis and therapeutic intervention through cystectomy and evacuation of haemoperitoneum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and serial haemoglobin measurements\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the evidence of significant ongoing bleeding and haemodynamic compromise. This approach could lead to further deterioration and the need for emergency surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpiric antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were signs of infection, but the clinical picture is consistent with bleeding rather than infection. The acute onset and ultrasound findings do not suggest a tubo-ovarian abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management with oral analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E would be suitable for a small, stable ovarian cyst without evidence of significant bleeding. However, this patient\u0027s clinical deterioration mandates immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransvaginal aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E of the cyst carries risks of infection and bleeding and would not address the existing haemoperitoneum. It is not indicated in the acute setting of a likely ruptured haemorrhagic cyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe differential diagnosis includes ectopic pregnancy and ovarian torsion, both of which would also require immediate surgical intervention. The negative pregnancy test makes ectopic pregnancy unlikely, while the ultrasound findings are more consistent with a ruptured haemorrhagic cyst than torsion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Haemorrhagic corpus luteum cysts can cause significant intraperitoneal bleeding requiring surgical intervention.","A negative pregnancy test with acute pelvic pain and free fluid suggests ruptured corpus luteum rather than ectopic pregnancy.","Haemodynamic instability or dropping haemoglobin with pelvic free fluid indicates need for surgical intervention."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Management of suspected ovarian masses in premenopausal women (Green-top Guideline No. 62) [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2011 [cited 2024 Nov 23]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/ovarian-masses-in-premenopausal-women-management-of-suspected-green-top-guideline-no-62/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93190"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16257"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93190"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-08T08:45:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-08T08:48:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8948"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111069"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attribu